04207nam a22007215i 9780814770467DE-B159720200608045044.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200608t20122012nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2012024948  a97808147704677 a10.18574/97808147704672doi  a(DE-B1597)547028  a(OCoLC)1027355703  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHV9104b.F443 2016 7aSOC0040002bisacsh04a363.25408309732231 aFeld, Barry C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aKids, Cops, and Confessions :bInside the Interrogation Room /cBarry C. Feld. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2012] 4cÂ©2012  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aYouth, Crime, and Justice ;v300tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tIntroduction -- t1. Interrogating Criminal Suspects -- t2. Questioning Juveniles -- t3. To Waive or Not to Waive -- t4. Police Interrogation -- t5. Juveniles Respond to Interrogation -- t6. Justice by Geography -- t7. True and False Confessions -- t8. Policy Reforms -- tAppendix 1. Data and Methodology -- tAppendix 2. Where the Girls Are -- tNOTES -- tREFERENCES -- tINDEX -- tABOUT THE AUTHOR 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aJuveniles possess less maturity, intelligence, and competence than adults, heightening their vulnerability in the justice system. For this reason, states try juveniles in separate courts and use different sentencing standards than for adults. Yet, when police bring kids in for questioning, they use the same interrogation tactics they use for adults, including trickery, deception, and lying to elicit confessions or to produce incriminating evidence against the defendants. In Kids, Cops, and Confessions, Barry Feld offers the first report of what actually happens when police question juveniles. Drawing on remarkable data, Feld analyzes interrogation tapes and transcripts, police reports, juvenile court filings and sentences, and probation and sentencing reports, describing in rich detail what actually happens in the interrogation room. Contrasting routine interrogation and false confessions enables police, lawyers, and judges to identify interrogations that require enhanced scrutiny, to adopt policies to protect citizens, and to assure reliability and integrity of the justice system. Feld has produced an invaluable look at how the justice system really works.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jun 2020) 0aJuvenile delinquentsxUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aJuvenile delinquentszUnited States. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration ofxUnited States. 0aJuvenile justice, Administration ofzUnited States. 0aPolice questioningxUnited States. 0aPolice questioningzUnited States. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertNYUP Backlist 2000-2013z978311070644440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780814770467423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780814770467.jpg  a978-3-11-070644-4  NYUP Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK